            <div class="response-definition two">
                <p>Bedsores (also known as decubitus ulcers, pressure ulcers or pressure sores) are one of the most common injuries in long-term care facilities.  According to the CDC, approximately 1 in 10 nursing home residents had a bedsore.  They develop when a resident is left in one position for too long and commonly form where bones are close to skin, such as the heel, ankle, tailbone, hip, shoulder, back, elbow, and back of the head.  Left unchecked serious infection can develop resulting in amputation, sepsis or death.  The law requires facilities to be proactive in preventing bedsores by keeping skin clean and dry, changing position and using pillows and products that relieve pressure, for example.  Thus, if your loved one is developing bed sores, it may be a sign that the nursing staff is neglecting its duties or not providing the appropriate level of care. </p>
